<TEXT>
people dressed as early colonists and american 
indians rushed aboard a ship and dumped boxes of tea into 
boston harbor on the 216th anniversary of the boston tea party 
the reenactment sunday evening of the colonials protest 
against british tariffs took on a modern twist as some of the 50 or 
so spectators wary of how the legislature might try to ease 
massachusetts budget problems shouted no new taxes 
under cover of night with temperatures in the low teens 15 to 
20 people hacked into tea boxes and threw the contents leaves 
instead of tea from the brig beaver ii into the harbor just as 
colonials did with 347 boxes in 1773 
nine redcoats then boarded the ship and escorted the 
colonials off to fife and drum music 
the tea party was a protest of british tariffs on the brew and 
englands practice of taxing colonial americans without allowing 
them representation in parliament the protest helped spark the 
revolutionary war less than two years later 
im a loyal revolutionary believing unjust taxes shouldnt be 
on something we can get for a cheaper price said joe kolb of 
watertown who has played a colonist in the reenactment since 1976 
ill be here as long as i can swing an ax said kolb a 
field investigator for a utility company 
we whipped the citizens into a frenzy about the tea and they 
decided to do something about it said john vann speaking as sam 
adams the ringleader of the original protest 
vann chairman of the massachusetts council of minutemen and 
militia wore colonial garb and a ponytailed wig 
he said the tea and debris from the boxes would be removed from 
the already polluted harbor by a boston tea party ship and museum 
employee in a canoe 
