<TEXT>
east german communists and opposition 
factions today resumed talks on the nations future over the din of 
hundreds of protesters who banged on windows and demanded a part in 
the negotiations 
the forum brought together various political parties social 
organizations and fledgling prodemocracy movements into a council 
of more than 40 that is to advise the interim government until free 
elections in may 
after two hours of debate participants decided to allow five 
more groups including the official trade union federation to take 
part in the talks and granted observer status to four more 
the negotiators agreed to meet each monday to propose 
legislation and proposed that future discussions be carried live on 
television and radio 
hundreds of angry demonstrators disrupted the first hour of the 
session using bullhorns to shout their demands to be included and 
banging on windows of the groundfloor conference room of the 
lutheran church building where the talks were held 
anyone who tries to force his participation in this way is not 
acting in the interests of democracy president manfred gerlach 
said as the noise overwhelmed speakers 
the participants proposed a message of solidarity to premier 
hans modrow and west german chancellor helmut kohl who meet 
tuesday in dresden 
they said the germangerman summit expresses the will of both 
nations to improve relations but they warned against any moves 
that would damage the sovereignty of either state a call to leave 
the reunification issue off the agenda 
the meeting comes a day after the communist party concluded an 
emergency congress in which it embraced a multiparty system and 
changed its name to the socialist unity party of germanyparty of 
democratic socialism 
the long title reflects both a new orientation to democratic 
principles and an eagerness to divorce itself from the corruption 
and power abuses that tainted former communist leaders ousted in a 
prodemocracy movement that began in september 
new communist party leader gregor gysi and wolfgang berghofer 
his chief deputy opened the talks dec 7 
at that session may 6 was set as the date for the firstever 
competitive elections to seat a new parliament kicking off a 
volatile campaign season likely to result in a minority role for 
the communists 
the talks have spurred the discredited communists to consult 
with their broadening opposition on how to run the country until 
elections are held 
in his address sunday to the congress final session gysi set 
out a new course for the party that breaks with four decades of 
stalinism 
nearly 2700 delegates unanimously approved the draft of a new 
statute to serve as the party rulebook until its next regular 
congress as well as the outlines of a new program 
the communists were stripped of their constitutional mandate to 
rule during a parliamentary session dec 1 it reduced their status 
to that of any other political force though the premier and much 
of his cabinet are communist 
when a new parliament is seated after elections it in turn will 
name a new government 
the communists polled only 12 percent support in a public 
opinion survey conducted by major west german pollsters in early 
december and modrow himself has predicted his party could win no 
more than 20 percent of the vote if elections were held now 
two other political conventions were held over the weekend by 
the small christian democratic union of east germany that is aiming 
to win votes from the religious population and by the opposition 
group democratic awakening 
despite the communists opposition to reunification the theme 
has taken hold among some political groups 
delegates at the founding party congress of democratic awakening 
in leipzig voted 35035 with 21 abstentions that the right of 
german unity should be inscribed in the east german constitution 
the christian democratic unions leader lothar de maiziere 
told delegates he could envisage a single german state within a 
united europe 
