local alumni of the depressionera 
civilian conservation corps are working to preserve the history of 
the group that built roads bridges dams and parks across the 
nation 
we want the nation to know from now to eternity what was done 
and show what a mark we made said james lynn of jacksonville he 
worked with the ccc in the ocala national forest and at fort clinch 
state park in fernandina beach from 1933 to 1938 
to make sure americans remember the work of the 3 million ccc 
members the local chapter of the ccc alumni will spend the next 
year compiling material for a book that will list and describe the 
work done by the organization 
the ccc formed by president franklin roosevelt directed an 
army of previously unemployed people who built parks roads dams 
and sewers and brought electricity and telephone service to 
millions 
kark busch program director of the local ccc alumni said no 
one has ever produced a complete listing of the corps works 
although various state and federal agencies have tried 
it will be a monumental task he said noting that in florida 
alone ccc members planted more than 18 million trees and built an 
estimated 2700 bridges 
the ccc did soil erosion control work on 23 million acres and 
strung 89000 miles of telephone line developed 80 parks and 
contributed 12 million mandays of work in fighting forest fires 
busch said 
it may take two books because we did so much he said 
making the task even more difficult busch said was that 
information on obscure projects may have to come from the people 
who worked on them 
