<TEXT>
after a kiss from his widow andrei d sakharov 
was buried monday in a snowy cemetery where kremlin elite joined 
with common people in mourning the human rights advocate once 
treated as an outlaw 
to the baleful strains of robert schumanns traumerai 
sakharovs coffin was carried along a path strewn with evergreen 
boughs to the freshly dug grave at vostryakovskoye cemetery 
its over sakharovs wife and dissident comradeinarms 
yelena bonner said as she turned to a companion during the 
twilight burial under pines dripping with rain 
sakharov died thursday of an apparent heart attack at the age of 
68 he was buried alongside bonners mother ruth a stalinera 
political prisoner who died in 1987 at age 87 
before the crimson and blacktrimmed coffin was lowered into 
the cold land sakharov tried so hard to change its lid was removed 
to allow bonner a last farewell she took the shroud from his face 
and bent to kiss him on the forehead 
as the procession wound its way through moscow some mourners 
marched alongside with signs demanding democratic elections one of 
sakharovs final causes 
others hoisted the blue red and white flag of czarist russia 
now the symbol of the grassroots prodemocracy russian peoples 
front 
top communist party brass riding sleek black limousines and tens 
of thousands of common people trudging through the slush joined in 
paying their last respects to the nobel peace laureate who once 
was pilloried as an ignoramus and dupe of the west 
in the morning president mikhail s gorbachev and other members 
of the ruling politburo stood in the rain to view the body outside 
the academy of sciences sakharov a creator of the soviet hydrogen 
bomb was a member of the academy 
gorbachev spoke at length there with bonner and later told 
reporters now it is clear that he deserved the nobel prize 
sakharov won the prize in 1975 for his human rights campaign 
but the soviet leadership at the time refused to let him go to 
norway to accept it he was hounded for years and finally sent into 
internal exile in gorky for nearly seven years 
an openended bus followed by thousands of mourners carried 
sakharovs body and bonner along lenin prospekt to outdoor funeral 
ceremonies in the parking lot of the luzhniki sports complex a 
favorite site for rallies by human rights activists 
more than 30000 people surged forward toward sakharovs 
carnationbedecked coffin and bonner had to plead for order 
sakharov did all he could ilya zaslavsky a moscow member 
of the congress of peoples deputies told the crowd now only 
his ideas can change things and only we can fulfill his ideas 
the academy of sciences is guilty before him we were passive 
in our defense of him sakharovs fellow academician and congress 
member dmitri likhachev said in a quavering voice now we say 
andrei dmitrievich forgive us 
staterun tv showed excerpts of the luzhniki services in a 
special broadcast of the kind usually reserved for the deaths of 
major government figures the evening news program vremya led 
off with an eightminute report on sakharovs last rites 
accompanied by a sorrowful dirge 
the 2250member congress or parliament to which sakharov 
belonged adjourned at midday so its members could attend the 
funeral ceremonies 
from luzhniki the coffin was transported nine miles in a bus to 
the cemetery along slushfilled streets 
in addition to gorbachev politburo members and other soviet 
leaders gathered at the academy of sciences to view sakharovs body 
from another direction buses escorted by police cars arrived 
some 20 people carried the casket on their shoulders from a bus and 
placed it on a bier in front of the academy bonner also emerged 
accompanied by her son alexei semenov 
the coffin was opened in the frigid rain and an umbrella opened 
to shield sakharovs face 
a bareheaded and somber gorbachev walked to the foot of the 
casket and stood for awhile in silence he bowed twice and the 
huddle of people around the casket broke up 
gorbachev and bonner spoke animatedly with bonner smiling at 
one point gorbachev and his entourage entered the academy 
presidium building to sign an official book of condolences he 
wrote simply ms gorbachev 
he emerged and talked briefly with reporters the relations 
between myself and sakharov were always those of mutual respect 
gorbachev said now it is clear that he deserved the nobel 
prize 
it was gorbachev who allowed sakharov to return to moscow in 
december 1986 after the years of exile in gorky the two men had 
clashed however over the speed and sweep of gorbachevs political 
reform program with sakharov demanding the communist party that 
gorbachev heads renounce its constitutional monopoly on power 
some parliamentarians monday pledged to heed sakharovs call to 
create a fullfledged opposition in the congress and to push for 
victory for progressives in nationwide local elections that began 
this month 
lech walesa the leader of polands solidarity movement and 
winner of the 1983 nobel peace prize had been expected to attend 
the service but polands official pap news agency reported his 
plane had to land in leningrad because of bad weather 
