the us government monday quadrupled to 2 
million the maximum reward it can offer to anyone who provides 
information that helps thwart an act of terrorism 
the money can be paid to any person who furnishes information 
that leads to the prevention frustration or favorable resolution 
of a terrorist act against us persons or property the state 
department said in a brief announcement 
the increase was made possible by a provision in an antidrug 
bill passed by congress and signed into law by president bush last 
week rewards had been limited to 500000 
we believe this increase will strengthen us efforts to 
prevent terrorist attacks and will help bring terrorists to 
justice the statement said 
anyone with information about planned terrorist acts should call 
the nearest us embassy or consulate if they are overseas or 
contact the fbi if they are in the united states it said 
the announcement came three days after the department issued an 
unusual public terrorism alert warning of the possibility of an 
attack on us targets in western europe or west africa 
concern for such an attack was based on recent reports of 
movement of terrorists from the middle east and the discovery of 
weapons shipments destined for proiranian groups in spain and 
africa 
it also reflected concern that terrorists might seek to use 
violence to observe the anniversaries of the dec 21 1988 bombing 
of pan am flight 103 or other attacks that have taken place during 
the holiday season 
