<TEXT>
police departments across the country 
routinely tape conversations between jailed suspects and their 
lawyers a congressional hearing was told monday 
the hearing by the courts subcommittee of the house judiciary 
committee grew out of a connecticut auto case that came to light 
earlier this year 
but state or local police or corrections officers in at least 12 
other states routinely record lawyerclient conversations said the 
subcommittee chairman rep robert w kastenmeier dwis 
a clear pattern is emerging across the country said 
kastenmeier it is unfortunate but likely that as we explore what 
happened in these states information about other states will come 
to light 
kastenmeier said information gathered by the subcommttee 
indicates that some form of bugging or wiretapping of conversations 
between jailed suspects and their attorneys has gone on in rhode 
island west virginia georgia new mexico oregon alaska 
wyoming vermont indiana utah nebraska and new jersey 
antonio califa legislative counsel to the american civil 
liberties union detailed several instances of police taping 
in rhode island state police since 1988 have taped incoming 
and outgoing calls on a system that connects the states five 
barracks according to califa the us attorney has begun a 
preliminary investigation 
in west virginia state police have been taping telephone 
conversations from suspects to their families and lawyers for 20 
years califa said callers are not warned that the calls are being 
recorded 
the utah civil liberties union is planning a lawsuit alleging 
that the state department of corrections routinely taped 
conversations between convicted prison inmates and their attorneys 
federal law forbids telephone taping except when investigatrs 
obtain a court order based on probable cause in a criminal 
investigation or when both parties to the conversation agree to the 
taping many state laws mirror the 1968 federal statute but some 
permit taping if only one party to the conversation consents 
mondays hearing included a videotape of a telephone 
conversation on august 5 1988 between a suspect in a connecticut 
vehicular homicide case and his attorney 
during trial a connecticut state police officer testified that 
the call was recorded as part of routine department policy 
an investigation by the hartford courant revealed that the 
secret taperecording by state police was widespread prompting 
gov william a oneill to order an immediate halt to the taping of 
attorneyclient calls the revelations cost public safety 
commissioner and state police commander lester j forst his job 
a later state investigation concluded that the tapes were not 
used to illegally gather evidence against suspects 
the connecticut state police have insisted from the start that 
the tapes were not listened to 
attorneys elliot b spector and marcia j gleeson representing 
connecticut and 19 defendants including two top former state police 
officials wrote to kastenmeier on saturday that the witness list 
for mondays hearing would only expose one side of the story 
the news media some public figures and criminal defense 
attorneys hysterically characterized these events as criminal acts 
amounting to a national crisis gleeson and spector wrote i 
would hope that the committee will take a more cautious approach to 
this issue 
gleeson said committee staff members rejected offers to provide 
an opposing point of view in the hearing 
members of kastenmeiers staff said the committee sought to 
question connecticut state police lt col john mulligan about the 
taping practices but that mulligan refused 
</TEXT>
