<TEXT>
the united states is formally protesting 
romanias weekend crackdown on protesters as a terribly mistaken 
course by a government that sees its popular support slipping 
away the state department said monday 
romanian police opened fire on protesters during weekend 
antigovernment riots and at least two people including a child 
were killed a person traveling in the region said an unconfirmed 
report in the west german media said hundreds were killed 
state department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said the violent 
clashes were the result of suppression of legitimate dissent by 
citizens frustrated with repression and hardships under the regime 
of president nicolae ceausescu among the last of the east blocs 
hardline communist rulers 
ceausescu has forcefully rejected reforms that are sweeping the 
rest of eastern europe 
since the government doesnt have the support of the people 
it is following a terribly mistaken course of using security forces 
to repress a serious manifestation of popular discontent with the 
policies of the ceausescu regime ms tutwiler told reporters at 
the departments daily briefing 
she said the us ambassador in bucharest alan green was 
determining what form our protest will take 
ms tutwiler noted that the united states has consistently 
criticized that regimes repression of dissent and denial of 
fundamental human rights to its people 
she said the united states was especially critical of 
authorities use of force against the rev laszlo toekes a 
reformed church minister in timisoara in western romania the 
unrest began saturday after his congregation sought to protect him 
from a courtordered move to another town ms tutwiler said 
the demonstration apparently grew in size and took on an 
antigovernment tone she said on sunday she said government 
security units brutally put down the demonstration with the use 
of truncheons tear gas and water cannons 
she said she could not confirm reports of casualties or of 
gunfire 
toekes an ethnic hungarian has championed the rights of other 
ethnic hungarians in the face of what they see as harassment by 
romanian authorities when the protest began saturday he was 
seeking to exercise legitimate religious rights ms tutwiler said 
the us embassy has been repeatedly rebuffed in its efforts to 
visit and talk with toekes because of security personnel deployed 
around his church and home she said 
we call upon the romanian government to cease its pressure 
against rev toekes and his congregation and allow him to exercise 
his fundamental freedom to communicate ms tutwiler said 
as to reports that hungary has sealed its borders in an effort 
to prevent news of the unrest from reaching the outside she said 
of course it would concern us and of course as in all the 
other countries we are for selfdetermination of those people this 
is no different in romania than it has been in any of the other 
countries where change has occurred in eastern europe 
