<TEXT>
a federal judge monday declared 
unconstitutional a 1976 regulation barring people from passing out 
leaflets in an area around the white house 
us district court judge john pratt issued the ruling in the 
case of a carol ann fennelly charged with illegally distributing 
pamphlets june 21 along east executive avenue between the white 
house and treasury department 
the material urged passersby to write members of congress in 
favor of housing for the homeless 
the judge said the regulation is an unconstitutional limitation 
on first amendment rights 
national park service regulations approved in 1970 were part of 
an effort to protect white house security by restrictions on 
demonstrations the 1976 amendments were drafted to preserve an 
atmosphere of calm and tranquility at memorials and buildings 
associated with past presidents 
in 1976 nothing was said about the underlying purpose of 
presidential security which was the overriding purpose of the 
comprehensive regulations issued in 1970 pratt said the 1970 
regulation allowed distribution of pamphlets and leaflets by not 
mentioning them 
in contrast the 1976 revision for the first time banned 
distribution of material in the white house park area the judge 
said 
pratt noted that fennelly would violate the regulation by 
passing out a leaflet but could convey the same identical 
message by word of mouth without fear of arrest 
a ban on the free distribution of leaflets and pamphlets in 
those remote areas far removed from the white house itself has no 
conceivable governmental interest pratt said in his opinion 
its distressing that the government continues to try to 
impose these ridiculous limitations on free speech in the nations 
capital said american civil liberties union lawyer arthur 
spitzer who handled the case 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

