romanian president nicolae ceausescu and 
his iranian counterpart hashemi rafsanjani began talks in tehran on 
monday to cement economic ties amid political turbulence in romania 
stirred by eastern europes reformist wave 
the islamic republic news agency said the two met shortly after 
ceausescu arrived on a threeday official visit it said further 
meetings were planned to bolster political and economic links 
ceausescu told rafsanjani i am pleased to be the first 
president to visit iran after your election tehran radio 
reported 
rafsanjani elected president in july assured ceausescu there 
are many fields of cooperation in boosting bilateral trade it 
added 
irna and the radio were both monitored in nicosia 
referring to ceausescus inflexibility while the political 
change surged through eastern europe irna praised romania as the 
sole east european country rigidly adhering to its past 
government 
ceausescu elected romanian communist party chief in 1965 is 
the longestserving leader in the soviet bloc 
he has stamped out almost all dissent in romania his crash 
industrialization program and his frantic efforts to repay all of 
romanias 11 billion debt have led to perennial shortages of 
consumer goods and rationing of basic foodstuffs 
on monday romania sealed its border with yugoslavia to all but 
official traffic after an antigovernment demonstration turned 
violent in timisoara west romania 
the iranian agency said others attending mondays talks in 
tehran were foreign minister ali akbar velayati vice president 
