the federal aviation administration was 
advised eight days before the bombing of pan am flight 103 that the 
us embassy in moscow was warning employees of a terrorist threat 
against pan am flights on the same route a presidential panel 
disclosed monday 
faa officials acknowledged that they had received a telex from 
the embassy on dec 13 1988 but said they did nothing about it 
even though they said it is against government policy to warn 
employees but not the general public of such threats 
the issue of a dual standard in warnings of potential terrorism 
is one of several being taken up by the sevenmember presidental 
commission on aviation security and terrorism which held its 
second hearing into the dec 21 1988 bombing over lockerbie 
scotland of flight 103 in which 270 people died 
the panel also received the results of a congressional report 
that said steppedup security measures since the disaster may be 
ineffective at highrisk foreign airports due to a lack of training 
standards 
the report by the general accounting office faults the faa for 
not establishing minimum training requirements for people who 
screen baggage and conduct other security operations at foreign 
airports 
kenneth mead gao director for transportation issues told the 
commission that the congressional watchdog agency has found several 
fundamental deficiencies in faa security programs 
earlier reports he noted had found problems with passenger 
screening airport security controls and security inspections 
mead said the faa has concurred with most of the agencys 
findings and made some changes but does not keep close enough tabs 
on security on a daily basis 
sen alfonse damato rny a commission member said the 
congressional studies indicate that the faa and the present 
system have flunked when it comes to providing basic security 
systems that anyone can have confidence in 
damato said problems with the faa suggest there may be a 
conflict between its role of promoting aviation and that of 
ensuring passenger safety 
