<TEXT>
the five presidents of the 
andean pact meeting on the remote galapagos islands agreed monday 
to help promote the integration of their countries economies and 
eventually use a common currency 
the presidents of ecuador colombia venezuela peru and bolivia 
signed the declaration of the galapagos in a ceremony in puerto 
ayora on the island of santa cruz 
presidents rodrigo borja of ecuador virgilio barco of colombia 
carlos andres perez of venezuela alan garcia of peru and jaime paz 
zamora of bolivia were to return to the ecuadoran mainland 600 
miles away before nightfall 
but first the leaders planned to visit several of the 
archipelagos islands to see the unique plant and animal life 
including giant tortoises land and marine iguanas seals and 
species of birds found nowhere else on earth 
upon their return to the mainland city of guayaquil late monday 
the four visiting presidents were scheduled to immediately fly home 
the five presidents arrived sunday in the galapagos and met in 
seclusion aboard a navy ship 
the document signed monday was prepared last week by the foreign 
ministers of the five nations meeting in guayaquil ecuadors most 
populous city and its primary port 
in the document the five presidents also agreed to forsake the 
use of force to resolve disputes among member nations of the 
andean pact and to abstain from actions against the territorial 
integrity of members 
in 1981 ecuador and peru fought a fourday border war it was 
sparked by ecuadors longstanding claim of sovereignty over a 
large tract of amazon jungle in northeastern peru 
the five presidents also signed a separate document in which 
they set goals they hoped to achieve in integrating their 
countries economies including a common currency no date for the 
common currency was divulged 
the creation of the european common market has indicated to us 
the direction in which the world is advancing perez said in a 
press conference in puerto ayoras municipal headquarters where 
the signing ceremony took place 
garcia called the galapagos summit the most important meeting 
the andean pact has had in its 20 years of existence 
in a press conference in guayaquil sunday before the presidents 
flew to the galapagos islands paz zamora said if we dont make 
a great effort the andean pact is going to die on us 
