a 72yearold native of byleorussia who emigrated 
to canada in 1951 has been charged under canadian war crimes 
legislation with the murder of 490 people the justice department 
said monday 
bill hobson chief of the departments war crimes unit said 
michael pawlowski was arrested at his home in renfrew about 60 
miles west of ottawa and was held pending a bail hearing 
hobson said charges filed in the supreme court of ontario 
specify eight counts of murder four under criminal code 
provisions dealing with war crimes and four with crimes against 
humanity 
the counts accuse pawlowski of murdering 410 jews and 80 
nonjewish poles in 1942 during world war ii in the byelorussian 
republic of the soviet union no mention was made as to whether 
pawlowski was serving in a military unit at the time 
he was charged with murdering 400 jews in the small village of 
snov 10 more jews who escaped the first killings and 80 poles in 
the same region 
pawlowski described as a horticulturist has lived in the 
renfrew area since coming to canada in 1951 five years later he 
became a canadian citizen 
under federal legislation passed two years ago canadian 
residents can be tried here for war crimes or crimes against 
humanity committed elsewhere 
the government has moved against two other people accused as war 
criminals since 1987 
the war crimes unit was set up after a royal commission 
recommended urgent action against 20 prime suspects who came to 
canada after world war ii 
