<TEXT>
subtle advertising constant sales periodic 
discounts and rebates and an abundance of consumer goods helped 
make big spenders of many americans in the decade of the 1980s 
now as if the abundance of choices were insufficient ordinary 
folks are likely to be presented with still another decision in the 
1990s they will be asked to decide between spending and saving 
it wont be easy after a 15year addiction to the retail 
marketplace a period in which the subtle arts of marketing along 
with plentiful credit and tax incentives helped produce a 
livefornow mentality 
uncle sam will be trying to break that habit in the 1990s and 
the government is preparing the first of its incentives a family 
savings account that would allow 5000 a year to be saved taxfree 
thats a big incentive but one many americans will find 
difficult to exploit because as envisioned those savings would 
lose their tax exemption if not maintained for a decade an 
eternity for those used to immediate gratification 
in this and other ways the bush administration hopes to 
accomplish two ends promote savings which are necessary for 
industrial development and job creation and spur americans to seek 
greater financial rewards by investing for the long term 
the consequences are enormous for individuals the general 
economy and government 
for individuals saving for the long term rather than immediate 
spending might provide the means to buy even more tomorrow 
investments grow the value of purchases often falls 
money saved generally means a sounder economy since it is 
invested in research and development of plant and equipment that in 
turn enhance productive efficiency more goods at lower cost and 
create jobs 
for government the return might not be immediate in fact tax 
exemptions can have the shortterm effect of reducing revenues but 
over the longer term a larger healthier economy inevitably means 
an increase in revenues 
whether the goals can be accomplished is made uncertain by many 
factors for one thing the family savings plan would involve a 
10year period of time an ambitious endeavor in a nation 
accustomed to making tax changes each year 
individual retirement accounts for example were originally 
meant to spur savings by allowing 2000 a year to be invested and 
deducted from current tax liability but after several years the 
deductibility feature was removed 
that action in the opinion of critics all but emasculated an 
otherwise strong incentive to save rather than spend it probably 
left a legacy of doubt about government promised that could impact 
the family savings plans 
however some of the other tax changes in recent years have been 
more in line with the need to save rather than spend most consumer 
debt for example no longer is tax deductible thus removing at 
least one incentive to spending 
americans accepted that action with amazing calmness even 
though it proved to be enormously costly to them however it 
didnt stop them from taking on debt and in that respect it failed 
to make a dent in the buynow philosophy 
it leaves this question if people feel so strongly about buying 
that they will pay higher taxes in order to continue buying will a 
program that rewards them for savings instead of buying be any more 
successful 
</TEXT>
