<TEXT>
cambodias noncommunist guerrillas 
are seeing an erosion of support from the western world at a time 
when they are making significant gains against the 
vietnamesebacked government in cambodia 
everywhere in the world the communist system is falling 
said gen sak sutsakarn commanderinchief of the khmer peoples 
national liberation front why wont the world support the 
noncommunists in cambodia especially cambodia we have suffered 
more than anyone 
the apparent reason for the diminishing support is a concern 
that the noncommunists are coordinating their military offensive 
with the communist khmer rouge which took power in 1976 and 
inflicted a reign of terror on cambodia that left a million or more 
dead 
the national liberation front the khmer rouge and a 
noncommunist group loyal to prince nordom sihanouk the former 
head of state have formed a loose alliance that has been waging 
war against the vietnamese and the cambodian government they 
installed in phnom penh the capital in 1979 
the coalition which holds cambodias seat in the united 
nations is largely armed by china but the two noncommunist 
factions get us and other western financial and political support 
the noncommunists still reel from charges of corruption 
internal bickering and being militarily inneffectual but they have 
established better internal discipline over the past two years and 
in recent months they have shown battlefield prowess 
in recent weeks a number of us congressmen have criticized 
washingtons support for the noncommunists as tantamount to 
support for the khmer rouge 
britain backed away from supporting the noncommunists in 
november following media reports that the british were training 
soldiers under the control of pol pot the shadowy khmer rouge 
leader who led cambodias terror government until a vietnamese 
ousted him in 1979 after they invaded the country 
australia and france have voiced support for leaving cambodias 
un seat vacant creating more cracks in what only months ago was 
a solid western bloc of support for the coalition 
all three groups seek either the downfall of the government of 
leader hun sen in phnom penh or leverage at the negotiating table 
but reporters able to reach battle zones or newly taken towns have 
seen no sign of joint military operations between the 
noncommunists and the khmer rouge 
with the bodies of government soldiers lying in nearby trenches 
national liberation front guerrillas celebrated their biggest 
victory of the war recently with the capture of svay chek a key 
town 
where are the khmer rouge said gen khun roeng pointing 
toward hundreds of his guerrillas on the defense perimeter the 
khmer rouge are not invited to this party 
resistance leaders acknowledge however that they do have field 
communication with the khmer rouge but solely for reasons of not 
getting in the way of each others attacks 
the noncommunists have seized more than 100 square miles of 
territory in northwest cambodia since launching a general offensive 
after vietnam began withdrawing its last troops from cambodia in 
september 
we have two enemies says gen dien del the national 
liberation fronts founder the first is the vietnamese and then 
the khmer rouge the cambodian people understand that vietnam wants 
to swallow our country and that is why all patriots have a duty to 
work together to save cambodia but we are not with the khmer 
rouge and the khmer rouge knows this very well 
he added we need the public support of the americans we 
need to be able to say look we are backed by the west 
sak the commanderinchief said what happens to cambodia if 
support for the noncommunist resistance stops the war will 
continue between the two communists the khmer rouge and the hun 
sen government there will be no peace but it guarantees the 
future government will be a communist one 
