<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission has 
withdrawn an appeal to a federal judges dismissal of its 
6yearold civil case against blinder robinson amp co inc 
officials said monday 
tom carter sec regional counsel said the withdrawal was filed 
dec 11 in the 10th us circuit court of appeals 
he declined to comment on the reason but said it had nothing to 
do with a separate disciplinary inquiry the sec has undertaken into 
the activities of blinder robinson a leading penny stock 
brokerage 
penny stocks are inexpensive shares of startup companies ranging 
from biotechnology research labs to energy and mining concerns the 
stocks usually are traded overthecounter and have been targeted 
by federal authorities as a frequent breeding ground for fraud 
the sec filed the civil case in april 1983 contending blinder 
robinson had failed to keep correct books and records and violated 
customer protection regulations 
in april us district judge lewis t babcock dismissed the 
case after determining the sec failed to comply with a court order 
and had not acted in good faith 
the judge also said the sec could not use documents or testimony 
obtained in the 1983 case in court against blinder robinson 
babcock said his ruling was justified by the secs egregious 
conduct in this case 
on dec 12 babcock ordered the sec to pay blinder robinson 
58575 in attorneys fees carter said 
in a news release issued monday blinder robinson executives 
said they are pleased that justice has been served by the award 
of attorney fees and costs to defendants 
carter said the sec is considering a possible appeal to the 
specific amount of the fees 
