<DOCNO> AP891218-0286 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a littleknown government agency created 11 
years ago to lend money to cooperative organizations has failed to 
adequately serve consumers since it was privatized by the reagan 
administration in 1982 a group affiliated with activist ralph 
nader charged monday 
the nader group center for study of responsive law charged at 
a news conference that the national cooperative bank has in effect 
used the subsidy from a lowinterest 1843 million federal loan to 
provide the profits necessary pay its executives high salaries and 
provide financial benefits to large cooperatives serving small 
businesses rather than consumers 
in 1988 only 5 percent of the banks 641 member cooperatives 
served businesses rather than individuals yet 30 percent of the 
banks 1996 milion in disbursements during the year were to the 
business cooperatives even though the law limits lending to 
business cooperatives at 10 percent of the total according to a 
report prepared for the nader group by seyoum a haregot 
the report also claimed the bank is not doing enough to serve 
lowincome consumers or to stimulate the formation of new 
cooperatives 
nader in a forward to the report said bank has abandoned its 
onecooperative one vote principle in favor of a voting system 
that gives control of the organization to large established 
cooperatives 
he said the banks managers drove it from serving ultimate 
consumers and toward a commercial banking model replete with 
executive emoluments all the while enjoying its substantial 
taxpayer subsidy 
the federal subsidy to the bank totaled 1195 million from 1982 
through 1988 according to haregots report salaries benefits and 
bonuses to the banks nine top executives totaled 13 million in 
1988 including 250000 to thomas s condit president and chief 
executive officer of the bank the report said 
in a written response linda r lewis corporate vice president 
of the bank said the salaries were in line with the pay of other 
financial institutions and said the bank has not been obligated to 
keep its pay comparable to government salaries since its 
privatization 
she said the bank disagreed with haregots argument that it lent 
too heavily to businessowned cooperatives saying that we 
believe a cooperative owned by a business is in fact owned by 
ultimate consumers 
also the bank at mid1989 had a lowincome loan portfolio of 
1318 million she said 
rep henry b gonzalez dtexas chairman of the house banking 
committee said he was deeply concerned about the failed 
promise of the bank and said it would be placed on the 
oversight agenda of the committee 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

