<TEXT>
boeing co engineers and scientists rejected a 
threeyear contract with the worlds largest commercial jet builder 
but technicians and support workers ratified a separate pact union 
leaders said monday night 
charles bofferding president of the seattle professional 
engineering employees association said members of the professional 
unit voted by 69 percent to reject their contract offer but also 
voted 52 percent against authorizing negotiators to call a strike 
it was the first time in the unaffiliated unions history that 
engineers and scientists rejected a contract offer he said the 
union consists of nearly 9300 of 15200 affected boeing scientists 
and engineers 
about 8300 of boeings nearly 12800 technical and support 
workers belong to the technical workers unit almost all of those 
covered by both contracts are in the puget sound area 
leaders of the engineers union will contact boeing officials 
immediately about returning to the table bofferding said 
we are critical parts of the boeing team and we affect them 
in all areas he said 
bofferding said the voting rate for both units exceeded 80 
percent a record the unions vote by mail 
the offers included general pay hikes totaling 3 percent for 
engineers and 7 percent for the lowerpaid technicians 
bofferding said he believed the main factor in the engineers 
rejection was the belief that the money package was too small 
compared with that won by boeing production workers in a 48day 
strike that ended last month 
the machinists threeyear pact includes pay increases of 4 
percent the first year 3 percent the next two years productivity 
bonuses of 10 percent 5 percent and 4 percent of annual gross pay 
and a boost in the costofliving formula from 86 percent of 
inflation to nearly 100 percent 
the offer to engineers who now make an average of nearly 
40000 a year called for a 3 percent wage increase and a 
productivity bonus of 10 percent of gross pay in the first year and 
no further general increases 
</TEXT>
